ce:section.ce:para:
Tobacco use, particularly cigarette smoking, accounts for approximately 5.4 million deaths each year. [1]. Smoking not only affects the active smoker but also harmful for passive smokers and the environment. Cigarette smoke is a complex mixed aerosol of about 5000 inorganic and organic components [2–4]. Nicotine, a pyridine-derived alkaloid, is a key component of cigarette smoke and poses significant risks to the lungs, reproductive system, heart, and kidneys. [5,6]. Tobacco-specific nitrosamines (TSNAs), polyaromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), and phenol are among the other constituents of cigarette smoke aerosol that are suspended as submicron-sized solid particles in addition to nicotine [7]. Along with these organic components, toxic metals like aluminum, lead, copper, chromium, cadmium, mercury, nickel, and zinc have also been found in cigarette smoke aerosol [8]. On another front, the need for cutting-edge energy storage solutions that are secure, economical, and sustainable is growing [9–11]. High power density (PD), stability, and rapid charging-discharging time make supercapacitor devices an ideal candidates to meet the demanding issues to some extent [12–14]. It is evident that the nanocarbon with a high surface area is a prime candidate for the development of cheaper and more efficient supercapacitor devices. [15,16]. Among nanocarbons, carbon dots (CDs), derived from biowastes, are being explored for the fabrication of environmentally friendly electrodes for supercapacitors [17,18]. Srivastava et al. has reported the synthesis of chemical-free biowaste-derived CDs for supercapacitor electrodes with a specific capacitance (C

                        sc
                     ) of 200 F/g, energy density (ED) of 17.78 W h/kg, and a high columbic efficiency within a potential limit of −0.55 V to +0.25 V in 2 M KOH electrolyte [17]. In another work, Jia et al. prepared biowaste-derived CDs-induced conductive, porous carbon for supercapacitor electrodes and reported decent areal capacitance of 2.8 F/cm2 at 10 A/g [18]. On the other hand, Lee et al. demonstrated the utilization of biowaste-derived N-doped CDs in biological applications [19].
